n(nums)\n        \n        # Start from the second last element and move to the first\n        for i in range(n - 2, -1, -1):\n            if nums[i] > nums[i + 1]:\n                # Calculate the number of parts we need to split nums[i] into\n                parts = (nums[i] + nums[i + 1] - 1) // nums[i + 1]\n                # The last number in the split should be as large as possible\n                nums[i] = nums[i] // parts\n                # Increment the number of operations by the number of splits minus one\n                operations += parts - 1\n        \n        return operations\n```\n\nThis solution works by iterating through the array from the second last element to the first. If an element is greater than the next element, it calculates how many parts the current element needs to be split into to ensure all parts are less than or equal to the next element. The number of operations is incremented by the number of splits minus one. This ensures that the array becomes sorted in non-decreasing order with the minimum number of operations.", "estimated_date": 1659225600000}